President Uhuru Kenyatta yesterday joined other leaders in pledging support to Somalia in dealing with the Shabaab terror group.Speaking at the inaugration of President Mohamed Abdullahi Farmajo, he said his administration will work with the new leader closely to build a new relationship and support the war on al Shabaab.&ldquo;We&rsquo;ll continue working with other countries that contribute Amisom troops and the international community to create an enabling environment for reconstruction, development and sustainable peace in Somalia,&rdquo; Uhuru said.Leaders of all Horn of Africa countries but Eritrea attended the event.They were Ethiopian Prime Minister Hailemariam Desalegn, Djibouti President Omar Guelleh and former Somalia President Hassan Sheikh Mohamud.Mohamud has been commended for having steered the country through a peaceful election and ensuring a smooth transition, despite losing to Mohamed.Uhuru commended Mohamud for the achievements his administration made in the last four years, especially the peaceful election and orderly transfer of power. &ldquo;The successful election and peaceful transfer of power are a clear demonstration of the desire and ability of the people of Somalia to strengthen governance structures and build sustainable peace,&rdquo; he said.Uhuru assured Farmajo that Kenya would remain steadfast in supporting efforts that would bring peace and stability in Somalia.He urged the Intergovernmental Authority on Development, the African Union and the international community to focus their attention on Somalia and offer necessary support to the new administration.Uhuru said all regional players must join hands to deal with external threats in the Horn of Africa, which is also experiencing severe drought.